default&#xa0;defaultCommunity caredefault&#xa0;defaultCare leaversdefault&#xa0;defaultYoung people leaving care are entitled to support from social services in many cases which can include 
defaultaccommodation.  They are also entitled to have that support set out in a Pathway Plan.  We act in a large number of cases where the local authority is refusing to accept responsibility for support or has not provided a proper Pathway Plan
default.
default A number of thes
defaulte are set out below.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultShe was accommodated by social services in February 2012.  Social
default services were well aware of the legislation, namely that she should in fact be accommodated under section 20 of the Children Act 1989, but they deliberately declined to do so, with the intention of avoiding duties to her as a care leaver, despite the obvi
defaultous need for it in her case, given the lack of familial support and the role that social services had to play in her childhood.
default&#xa0;
defaultAfter extensive negotiations, the local authority conceded without the need to issue.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultRT was left to fend for himself, and ended up being taken in by a landlady who was not able to provide him with appropriate care and support.
default&#xa0;
default Two years later we were approached in order to try to ensure that RT was receiving lawful support.
default&#xa0;
default This involved
default going over the social services’ records for the preceding two and a half years, to identify what failures had been made.
default&#xa0;
default The level of work required was extensive and in no way feasible within an artificially capped limit on costs to be paid.  We were abl
defaulte to successfully get a lawful support plan and care package in place for RT, in order to move him to an appropriate placement.
default&#xa0;
default 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultA charity referred the case to us. We sought to get her support 
default              
defaultreinstated.  The local authority did not back down and (unsurprisingly) ran a delay argument.  We issued a judicial review, with detailed witness st
defaultatements from the client, ourselves, and the charity dealing with the delay point.  Permission was refused on the grounds of delay. We renewed, and after a very tough hearing were able to persuade a judge to make an exception from the normal three month ru
defaultle and grant permission.  The case then subsequently settled very favourably for our client, but in order to secure a favourable settlement, we settled on the basis of no order as to costs.
default&#xa0;
defaultThere is no way that a case such as this would be brought in the 
defaultfuture if the current judicial review proposals are implemented, as no firm would run the risk of getting knocked out on permission and 
defaultthen 
defaultnot 
defaultbeing 
defaultpaid at all, even though the underlying case was good. 
default&#xa0;
defaultCivil merits test – removing legal aid for bordedefaultrline casesdefault&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultAlternative solutionsdefault&#xa0;defaultSome years ago, the Legal Services Commission   consulted on the possibility of restricting legal aid for judicial review to those firms and organisations that had a demonstrable track record of success and expertise or who had staff who could show this. 
default 
defaultWhile it was rejected at the time, the climate may now be right for the introduction of this to ensure that the Court’s time is not wasted by badly prepared applications and legal aid money is not wasted on frivolous applications
default. This would resolve many o
defaultf the issue the Government has said its proposals are intended to address.
default&#xa0;
