defaulte supposed “Impact Assessment”. 
default We estimate that virtually all of our cl
defaultients in our recent education judicial review cases have protected characteristics and are vulnerable and some 70% of those in community care cases.  Even where the client does not have a protected characteristic, they are almost invariably  vulnerable as 
defaultthey will be young people who 
defaultare or 
defaulthave been in care and are nearly always in extremely deprived and difficult circumstances.  
defaultOn the face of it these proposals seem discriminatory in themselves.  
defaultThe proposals on paying for work up to obtaining 
defaultpermission
default would seriously affect their interests as it is highly likely that 
defaultmany
default providers will be extremely reluctant to take on cases other than those that 
defaultare
default absolutely certain of success, and then only if the amount of work which is carried out, can
default be done at half the current time levels.  In addition, many providers will simply be unable to act pro bono in effect in these cases.  Provision for this group which is already low, wi
defaultll
default diminish further as local authorities realise that there is little e
defaultffective control over their actions.
